Subject: [PATCH] =?UTF-8?q?perf=20wave=2021=20patch=200094=20=E2=80=94=20L?=
 =?UTF-8?q?ever=20G=20fix:=20Organya=20stereo-vs-mono=20mismatch?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

DOS-PORT (patch 0094, Phase 9 wave 21 Lever G fix). Closes the audio
quality regression surfaced by W21A real-HW measurement: Tier-2
(AUDIO_CHANNELS=1) audio played slow + distorted, blocking 0093
default-flip.

Bug diagnosis:

`Song::Synth()` always produces stereo-interleaved samples (L/R at
samples[p*2+0] / samples[p*2+1] at Organya.cpp lines ~325-326)
regardless of `AUDIO_CHANNELS`. The pre-0094 `_musicCallback` copies
`samples[]` LINEARLY into the audio device's output stream. When SDL
device is mono (Tier-2), it interprets `L,R,L,R,...` as MONO FRAMES
→ playback steps through the synth buffer at HALF the intended rate
→ music plays at half speed + sub-Nyquist aliasing distortion.

Why this slipped through 0092: the patch correctly substituted
AUDIO_CHANNELS at the SDL audio device spec (SoundManager.cpp:91)
and at all 9 Pixtone resample-spec sites (which use SDL_AudioStream
conversion paths that handle mono/stereo correctly). It missed the
Organya-internal-stereo assumption because the synth's stereo
interleave is hardcoded into the per-tone panning math at lines
325-326, NOT at any SDL spec site that the spec audit flagged.

NOT a phase-math bug, NOT a stale SAMPLE_RATE capture. The
sampling_rate at line 187 correctly captures the runtime SAMPLE_RATE
(post SoundManager::init flips it). Phase-inc computations at lines
222/229 use the captured value correctly.

Why the W21A fps measurement was inflated:

Half-speed playback meant `Synth()` refilled the synth buffer half as
often per real second → audio_mix CPU work distributed over 2× as
long → per-callback measurement showed 0.40 ms vs Tier-1's 6.55 ms
(94% reduction). That was a measurement artifact of the bug, not a
real CPU saving.

Post-0094, audio_mix per-call cost will rise (mono-downmix adds an
L+R average per output sample), so the fps gain measured in W21A
(-26.6 ms/flip, above predicted upper bound -22) will fall back into
the spec's predicted range (-3 to -22 ms/flip). Still positive
(IRQ-rate halving + reduced data still apply), just not the inflated
buggy figure.

Fix:

Mono-downmix at the `_musicCallback` boundary. Synth stays internally-
stereo (the per-tone L/R panning math at lines ~325-326 depends on
producing two independent channels; rewriting synth would be
invasive + lose the stereo separation in Tier-1 too). The callback
gets a branch:

  Tier-1 (AUDIO_CHANNELS == 2): linear copy of synth samples
                                (bit-identical to pre-0094).
  Tier-2 (AUDIO_CHANNELS == 1): average synth's interleaved L/R pair
                                into one mono sample per output frame;
                                each output frame consumes 2 synth
                                entries (idx += 2 vs Tier-1's idx++).

Bounds check on R-channel index: defensive belt-and-braces in case
idx wraps to an odd value (synth.Synth() always produces an even
number of samples, so idx+1 < size when idx is even, but the existing
`if (idx >= song.samples.size())` guard only checks idx — not idx+1).
Pathological fallback uses L value if R would OOB.

Audit re-confirmed clean for other rate / channel hardcoding:

- `22050` literal in Organya.cpp / Organya.h: none (besides my own
  comment at line 478 that references the .pxt on-disk format).
- `* SAMPLE_RATE` / `/ SAMPLE_RATE` patterns: only the 2 phase-inc
  sites at 222/229 which use `sampling_rate` (captured runtime
  value, not stale).
- Bit shifts encoding power-of-2 rate ratios: none found.
- Pixtone clean: uses SDL_AudioStream conversion path (line 681
  dst_spec = { S16, AUDIO_CHANNELS, SAMPLE_RATE }); SDL handles
  mono/stereo conversion automatically. No internal stereo-
  interleave in Pixtone's data path.
- OGG clean: SDL3 OGG decoder auto-resamples to whatever device
  config is set (per docs/PHASE9-LEVER-G-PLAN.md § 2.6).

The "Organya phase math has a hardcoded SAMPLE_RATE" hypothesis (per
team-lead's diagnostic direction) was a good first guess but the
issue was actually a CHANNEL-COUNT mismatch at the callback boundary.
Symptom (slow + distorted) is identical for both root causes.

Slot 0094 (NOT amend 0092) per the two-stage rollout pattern: keeps
0092 as the working-modulo-this-bug baseline; if 0094 surfaces a
regression the rollback is just dropping 0094 alone. Mirrors
0086→0088 / 0085 polarity-flip / 0087+ext patterns.

Test plan:
- DOSBox-X smoke (build-qa): verify Tier-2 init clean, audio plays
  without crash. Subjective audio A/B in DOSBox-X is approximate
  (audio path is similar to real HW but not identical); real-HW
  validation is the load-bearing test.
- Real-HW iter W21B (realhw): single-PLAY at Tier-2 (env stack
  matches W21A2). Operator listens to title attract music + first-
  room ambient + SFX + music+SFX overlap per
  docs/PHASE9-LEVER-G-PLAN.md § 4 canonical scene checklist.
- If "acceptable / borderline" verdict: 0095 ships default-flip
  (mirrors 0092 → would-be-0093 / 0086 → 0088 pattern).
- If "unacceptable": investigate further (could be the simple-average
  downmix loses too much spectral content; alternatives are
  max-of-L/R, weighted-by-pan, or single-channel synth which would
  be a more invasive rewrite).

Reference:
  patches/nxengine-evo/0092-perf-wave-21-lever-g-tier2-audio-config.patch
